<TITLE> Four killed in Indian riots over tribal quotas </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 JAIPUR, India, May 29 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Four people were killed in western India on Tuesday after police opened fire on ethnic Gujjars who blocked a highway to demand special status as a tribe to gain government jobs and places in educational institutions. Two policemen were also missing after the riot near Jaipur, the capital of Rajasthan province, senior police officer Madhukar Gupta said. Thousands of people belonging to the Gujjar ethnic community gathered on the main highway and blocked traffic. The Gujjars are demanding the status of a "scheduled tribe" which under Indian law would benefit them with government jobs and education opportunities. The issue of job and education quotas for lower castes and tribal peoples has often sparked controversy and protests in India. Last year, dozens of medical students were injured in clashes with police as they protested against a government plan to reserve some seats at universities for lower castes and tribals
